entries.meaning: (graph theory) An outgoing edge in a digraph, i.e. one that leaves a particular node.

verbs.description: outedge (third-person singular simple present outedges, present participle outedging, simple past and past participle outedged)

examples: The naked mollusca are those in which the mantle is simply membranous or fleshy: most frequently, however, it forms in its thickness one or several laminae, of a substance more or less hard, deposited in layers, and increasing in extent, as well as in thickness, because the recent layers always outedge the old ones.
